  1. Exploring the Data The data explored below includes records of all areas owned and managed by the United States’ National Park Service. The data is broken out by region, park name, and park type. For each location, the Park Service has tracked the number of recreation visits to that location, as well as the various ways in which people spend the night in the park, from backcountry or tent campers, to RV campers or concessioner lodging. Exploring the data set allows us to better understand the size of our data set and the variables that are included. There are a number of different ways to view the data, each of which is outlined below.

2.1 Cleaning the Data It’s important to clean the data to make sure all variable names appear as desired and are intuitive for any person who may be looking at the data or research product. Someone should be able to understand what they’re looking at without necessarily being very familiar with the data.

2.1 Cleaning the Data Part 1: Correcting Variable Names

#These commands correct the variable names:
names(Parkdata)=gsub("\r\n", " ", names(Parkdata))
names(Parkdata)=gsub(" ", "_", names(Parkdata))
#Test to see that names have been corrected
names(Parkdata)
##  [1] "Region"                        "Park_Name"                    
##  [3] "Park_Type"                     "Recreation_Visits"

##  [7] "Tent_Camping"                  "RV_Campers"                   
##  [9] "Backcountry_Campers"           "Non-recreation_Overnight_Stay"
## [11] "Misc._Overnight_Stay"

repeated='Klondike Gold Rush'
Parkdata[(Parkdata$Park_Name ==repeated) & (Parkdata$Region =='Pacific West Region'),]
## # A tibble: 1 x 11
##                Region          Park_Name              Park_Type
##                 <chr>              <chr>                  <chr>
## 1 Pacific West Region Klondike Gold Rush National Historic Park
## # ... with 8 more variables: Recreation_Visits <dbl>,
## #   Concessioner_Lodging <dbl>, Concessioner_Camping <dbl>,
## #   Tent_Camping <dbl>, RV_Campers <dbl>, Backcountry_Campers <dbl>,
## #   `Non-recreation_Overnight_Stay` <dbl>, Misc._Overnight_Stay <dbl>
repeated='Klondike Gold Rush'
Parkdata=Parkdata[!((Parkdata$Park_Name ==repeated) & (Parkdata$Region =='Pacific West Region')),]

compressedMap_alaska="https://github.com/alexaschreier/PROJECT/raw/master/Alaskaframe2.zip"
temp=tempfile()
download.file(compressedMap_alaska, temp)
unzip(temp)
(maps=list.files(pattern = 'shp'))
## [1] "alaskaframe (1).shp" "capital.shp"         "intermountain.shp"  
## [4] "midwest.shp"         "northeast.shp"       "pacificwest.shp"    
## [7] "southeast.shp"
alaska_zipMap <- rgdal::readOGR("alaskaframe (1).shp",stringsAsFactors=F)
## OGR data source with driver: ESRI Shapefile 
## Source: "alaskaframe (1).shp", layer: "alaskaframe (1)"
## with 1 features
## It has 9 fields
## Integer64 fields read as strings:  ALAND AWATER
names(alaska_zipMap)
## [1] "STATEFP"  "ANRCFP"   "ANRCNS"   "AFFGEOID" "GEOID"    "NAME"    
## [7] "LSAD"     "ALAND"    "AWATER"
plot(alaska_zipMap)

library(RColorBrewer)
library(classInt)
numberOfClasses = 3
colorForScale='YlGnBu'
colors = brewer.pal(numberOfClasses, colorForScale)
intervals <- classIntervals(varToPlot, numberOfClasses, 
                            style = "quantile",
                            dataPrecision=2)
colorPallette <- findColours(intervals, colors)
legendText="Count of visits"
shrinkLegend=0.7
title="Alaska Region"

plot(alaska_zipMap,col='white',main=title)
plot(AlaskaMap, col = colorPallette,border=NA,add=TRUE)
legend('topright', legend = names(attr(colorPallette, "table")), 
       fill = attr(colorPallette, "palette"), cex = shrinkLegend, 
       bty = "n",
       title=legendText)
